{"action": "patch", "name": "ecommerce-codebase-audit", "old_string": "## Auth Flow & Cookie Debugging", "new_string": "## Product SEO: generateMetadata Pattern

Every e-commerce product page needs dynamic `generateMetadata` for search engines and social sharing. The pattern is non-obvious when products are fetched client-side (useEffect from Supabase) rather than server-side.

### The Problem

In most Next.js e-commerce apps, product pages are client components that fetch data via `useEffect` from Supabase. This means:
- No server-side `<title>` or `<meta>` tags — pages get the default layout metadata
- Social shares (WhatsApp, Facebook, Twitter) show generic OG tags, not the product info
- Google sees no product-specific title/description

### The Pattern

Create a server-side `export async function generateMetadata` in `app/producto/[slug]/page.tsx` that fetches product data independently of the client component:

```tsx
import { createClient } from "@ai-whisperers/auth/supabase/server"
import type { Metadata } from "next"

const staticProducts = c.home?.productCatalog?.products || []

function slugify(s: string) {
  return s.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z0-9áéíóúñü]+/g, "-").replace(/-+$/, "")
}

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: { params: Promise<{ slug: string }> }): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { slug } = await params
  let name = "", description = "", imageUrl = "", price = ""

  // Try DB first — fetch all and match by slugified name
  try {
    const supabase = await createClient()
    const { data: allData } = await supabase.from("ej_products").select("name, description, image_url, price")
    if (allData) {
      const match = allData.find((p: any) => slugify(p.name) === slug)
      if (match) {
        name = match.name
        description = match.description?.substring(0, 160) || match.name
        imageUrl = match.image_url
        price = match.price
      }
    }
  } catch {}

  // Fallback to static content JSON
  if (!name) {
    const staticProd = staticProducts.find((p: any) => slugify(p.name) === slug)
    if (staticProd) {
      name = staticProd.name
      description = (staticProd.description || staticProd.name).substring(0, 160)
      imageUrl = staticProd.imageUrl || ""
      price = staticProd.price
    }
  }

  if (!name) return {}

  return {
    title: `${name} | Store Name — Tagline`,
    description,
    openGraph: {
      title,
      description,
      url: `https://store.com/producto/${slug}`,
      type: "product",
      images: [{ url: imageUrl || "/images/og-default.webp", width: 1200, height: 630, alt: name }],
    },
    twitter: { card: "summary_large_image", title, description, images: [...] },
    other: { "product:price:amount": price, "product:price:currency": "PYG" },
  }
}
```

### Key Techniques

1. **slugify() matching** — Most small e-commerce DBs don't have a `slug` column. Products are matched by slugifying the `name` field client-side. The server-side metadata function must use the same algorithm.

2. **DB → Static fallback** — Try Supabase first (has the most current data), fall back to static content JSON. Never show a product page without metadata.

3. **Empty return** — If no product found for the slug (e.g., invalid URL), return `{}` — Next.js falls back to root layout metadata cleanly.

4. **`params` is a Promise** — Next.js 15+ requires `await params`. Important for both `generateMetadata` and the default page export.

5. **Price as meta tag** — Add `other: { "product:price:amount", "product:price:currency" }` so social platforms and price comparison tools can extract it.

6. **OG image fallback** — Use `.webp` format in the fallback image path (not `.png`) to save bandwidth.

### Verification

```bash
# Check metadata is live
curl -s https://store.com/producto/some-product | grep -oP '<title>[^<]+</title>'
curl -s https://store.com/producto/some-product | grep -oP '<meta property="og:title"'
curl -s https://store.com/producto/some-product | grep -oP '<meta property="product:price:amount"'
```

### Pitfalls

- **Don't use `.single()` on the Supabase query** — unless there's a unique `slug` column. If multiple products could match (and they won't with slugify name matching), `.single()` throws. Use `.select("*")` + `find()` in JS instead.
- **Don't throw on error** — The `catch {}` swallows DB failures silently. If DB is down, the static fallback still works. This is intentional for SEO — missing metadata is worse than stale metadata.
- **Price format** — If prices are stored as formatted strings ("Gs. 450.000"), pass them as-is to `product:price:amount`. Social platforms parse numeric values from the beginning of the string.

## Brand Filter Pattern

When an e-commerce site has a product catalog with brands but no brand filter, add one in the `SearchAndFilters` component:

### Implementation

```tsx
// State
const [brandFilter, setBrandFilter] = useState("")

// Extract unique brands from product data (memorized)
const brands = useMemo(() => {
  const b = new Set<string>()
  products.forEach((p: any) => { if (p.brand) b.add(p.brand) })
  return Array.from(b).sort()
}, [products])

// Filter logic
if (brandFilter) {
  result = result.filter((p) => p.brand === brandFilter)
}

// Dependency array
// Add `brandFilter` to useMemo dependency array

// UI — insert between Category and Sort dropdowns
{brands.length > 0 && (
  <div>
    <label className="mb-1 block text-xs font-medium text-muted-foreground">Marca</label>
    <select value={brandFilter} onChange={(e) => setBrandFilter(e.target.value)}
      className="w-full rounded-lg border border-input bg-background px-3 py-2.5 text-sm">
      <option value="">Todas</option>
      {brands.map((brand) => (
        <option key={brand} value={brand}>{brand}</option>
      ))}
    </select>
  </div>
)}
```

### Key Points

- Brands are extracted dynamically from product data — no hardcoded brand list
- Brands dropdown is conditionally rendered: only show when there are brands to filter
- The grid layout may need to expand from 5 to 6 columns to fit the brand dropdown
- Brands are sorted A-Z for consistent UX

